# Logging Conventions

## Log Levels

| Level | When to Use |
|-------|-------------|
| `debug` | Verbose info useful during development only |
| `info` | Normal operations worth noting (startup, connections) |
| `warn` | Recoverable issues, degraded performance |
| `error` | Failures requiring attention |

## Backend (NestJS Logger)

```typescript
import { Logger } from "@nestjs/common";

@Injectable()
export class MyService {
  private readonly logger = new Logger(MyService.name);

  async doSomething(): Promise<void> {
    this.logger.debug("Starting operation");
    this.logger.log("User registered", { userId });  // info level
    this.logger.warn("Retrying bot connection", { botId, attempt });
    this.logger.error("Database query failed", error.stack);
  }
}
```

## Frontend (logger utility)

```typescript
import { logger } from "../utils/logger";

logger.debug("Rendering component", "GameView", { tableId });
logger.info("Connected to WebSocket", "WebSocket");
logger.warn("Reconnecting...", "WebSocket", { attempt: 3 });
logger.error("Failed to load", error, "TournamentStore", { id });
```

## What to Log

**Do log:**
- Service startup/shutdown
- External service connections (DB, Redis, WebSocket)
- Authentication events (login, logout, failed attempts)
- Business events (tournament started, game finished)
- Errors with stack traces and context

**Don't log:**
- Sensitive data (passwords, tokens, full card hands)
- Every routine operation (each HTTP request — use metrics instead)
- Large objects (log IDs, not full entities)

## Structured Context

Include relevant IDs for tracing:

```typescript
// Good: includes context for debugging
this.logger.log("Hand completed", { gameId, handNumber, winnerId });

// Bad: no context
this.logger.log("Hand completed");
```

## Production vs Development

- Frontend: Debug logs only show in dev mode (`import.meta.env.DEV`)
- Backend: Control via `LOG_LEVEL` env var
- Errors in production should report to Sentry (when integrated)
